SIMPLE: precarious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Precarious
<hw>Pre*ca"ri*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>precarius</ets> obtained by begging or prayer, depending on request
or on the will of another, fr. <ets>precari</ets> to pray, beg. See
<er>Pray</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Depending on the will or pleasure
of another; held by courtesy; liable to be changed or lost at the
pleasure of another; <as>as, <ex>precarious</ex> privileges</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Held by a doubtful tenure; depending on unknown
causes or events; exposed to constant risk; not to be depended on for
certainty or stability; uncertain; <as>as, a <ex>precarious</ex> state
of health; <ex>precarious</ex> fortunes.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Intervals of
partial and <xex>precarious</xex> liberty.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Uncertain; unsettled; unsteady; doubtful;
dubious; equivocal.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Precarious</er>,
<er>Uncertain</er>. <xex>Precarious</xex> in stronger than
<xex>uncertain</xex>. Derived originally from the Latin
<xex>precari</xex>, it first signified ⟦ldquo⟧granted to
entreaty,⟦rdquo⟧ and, hence, ⟦ldquo⟧wholly dependent on the will of
another.⟦rdquo⟧ Thus it came to express the highest species of
uncertainty, and is applied to such things as depend wholly on future
casualties.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Pre*ca"ri*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Pre*ca"ri*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precation</ent>⟦br⟧
